{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/0028060494A/1949040801/0465.xml":{"full_text":"New Ruling Excludes\nDank Directors From\nEmploye Tax List\nBy Edword C. Stone\nThe Commissioner of Internal\nRevenue has reversed a long\nstanding ruling and announced\nthat bank directors wHo serve on\ncommittees appointed by the\nboard or under the by-laws of the\nbank, are not to be treated as em\nployes for Social Security tax\npuposes.\nThe effect of this important\nruling is to exclude such directors\nfrom the count of employes in de\ntermining whether the bank is\nsubject to the Federal employment\ntax as an employer of eight or\nmore individuals.\nFull details of the ruling have\nbeen sent to all state secretaries\nby D. J. Needham, general counsel\nof the ABA.\nHyatt Heads Bank Group.\nHerbert 8. Hyatt, cashier. Bank\nof Demascus and vice president of\nthe Montgomery Bankers' Associa\ntion, has been elected chairman\nof Group 2, Maryland Bankers\u2019\nAssociation. At 32. he is believed\nto be the youngest man to hold\nthis office.\nRichard E. Eckel of the North\nwestern Mutual Life Insurance Co.\nand John H. Rick. Acacia Mutual,\nhave been awarded the Chartered\nLife Underwriter designation by\nthe American College of Life!\nUnderwriters.\nThe new Philadelphia-Balti\nmore Stock Exchange reports a\nvery sharp gain in the volume of\ncombined trading. Many Wash\nington Stock Exchange ideas are\nbeing used to excellent advantage.\nJames M. Thurmond, former\nlieutenant in charge of the United\n8tates Naval School of Music, has\nbeen made executive assistant to\nEarle C. Campbell, head of the\nCampbell Music Co. He has a\nIrilliant musical record.\nThe Second National Bank re\norts total deposits of $28,821,574\nB March 31 against $29,089,408\nt the end of December.\nWeather Cuts Gas Net\nNet earnings of the Washington\nras Light Co. in February were\nit hard by warm weather, $284,\n09 comparing with $427,845, a\n_ screase of $142,938. Net income\n?ln the two months totaled $583.\n'036 against $682,327, a drop of\nf99.291.\nV Trading will be resumed in\nNational Bank of Washington\nstock on the Washington Stock\n^Exchange tomorrow, following to\n-day\u2019s announcement that new\nInterests have bought control of\nthe bank. Substantially more\nthan 51 per cent of the stock\nwas deposited at the Liberty\nNational Bank, the offer expiring\nthis afternoon. The buyers have\nnot been disclosed. The historic\nname remains unchanged.\nPotomac Electric 3.60 preferred\n\"A\u2019\u2019 stock was traded on the\nWashington Exchange yesterday\nat 47, following \"lifting'\u2019 of ther\nredemption plan.\n^Bu&ness Briefs I\nMoney in Circulation expanded\nto $27,514,000,000 on April 6, a\ngai*t of $111,000,600 from a. week\ncarfiEvibut. remained $3i9^6o,ooo\nbeta* a year earlier\u2014Federal Tte\n\u00aberv\u00ab\u201cSoard/\nDepartment Store Sales in the\nweek ended April 2 rose 8% above\nthe like 1948 week\u2014Federal Re\nserve Board. It was the first year\nto-year gain since January.\nIron and Steel Payrolls in Feb\nruary approximated $189,751,000,\na record for the month, and 13%\nabove the same 1948 month\u2014\nAmerican Iron Steel Institute.\nEmployment of 652,800 set a new\npostwar high and was 2.600 above\nthe previous month.\nSharp Dohme, Inc., directors\nvoted to offer for sale 208.373\nshares of additional common stock\nto finance new construction.\nGeneral Motors Corp. reported\nits United States and Canadian\nfactories built 570,692 cars and\ntijucks in the first 1949 quarter\nvs, 547,017 in the same 1948 period.\n(Farnsworth Television Radio\nCorp. sale to Inemation&l Tele\nphone Telegraph Corp. has been\nendorsed by Senator Home E.\nCfcpehart, a Farnsworth spokes\nr|An said. The Senator no longer\nhfcs any connection with Farns\nworth.\n'Lehman Corp. reported net as\nsist value of $47.24 a share on\nMarch 31 vs. $46.57 on December\nM and $50.22 on June 30 last\nyfar.\nGamble-Skogmo, Inc., sales for\nMarch amounted to $11,623,400. a\ncweline of 6.9% from a year\nearlier; for three months. $26,\n935,600, a decrease of 12.9%.\nButler Brothers sales in March\ntotaled $11,241,553. a drop of\n19.38% from a year earlier; in\nthree months, $29,913,299, a de\ncline of 18.3%.\nJ. J. Newbury Co. sales for\nMarch amounted to $9,645,912, a\ndecrease of 8.4% from a year\nearlier; for three months, $25,\n594,676, a gain of 1.6%.\nMercantile Stores Co. sales in\nMarch totaled $8,921,800, a drop\nof 9% from a year earlier; in two\nmonths ended March 31, $18,028,\nftX), a decrease of 5.9%.\nLane Bryant, Inc., sales in\nMarch totaled $5,216,374, a decline\nof 4.3% from a year earlier; in\nthree months, $12,360,262, a drop\nof 3.7%.\n\u2014\"American Gas A Electric Co.\nearned $21,073,613 or $4.54 a share\nin 12 months ended February 28\n1119,688.141 or $4.23 in the pre\nus year.\nVirginian Railway and subsidi\nr had net income of $7,073,883\n$4.31 in 1948 vs. $7,282,162 or\n48 in 1947.\ngeneral Outdoor Advertising\nearned $2,584,365 or $4.07 in\n18 vs. $2,371,387 or $3.72 in the\nivlous year.\nFalconbridge Nickel Mines, Ltd.,\n1 income for 1948 was $1,502,099\n44 cents vs. $824,071-or 24 cents\nin 1947.\nSimplicity Pattern Co. profit for\n.1948 was $874,552 or $1.18 vs.\n$862,035 or $1.16.\nVenesuelan Petroleum Co. earn\ned $4,575,599 or $1.14 in 1948 vs.\n$4,235,587 or $1.06.\nWoodward Iron Co. net income\nfor three months ended March 31\nwas $1,678,311 or $2.38 vs. $1,061,\n838 or $1.50 in the same 1948 pe\nnWs\nN. Y. STOCK EXCHANGE\n(TtnU(4 Or tht tmriiUS Pim i\nStock .dc Add ltd\nDividend Rata 00 Blab. Low l.Ti chic\nABBOTT L2 \u00ab\u00bba 7 79-4 7*1* 7*5* V*\nA C P-Brli) Mot a J'\u00bb 2*\u00bb 7*4\nAcme Steel 4 1 *6*\u00bb e**4 Mh -4\nAdams Eg 1 10* 4 1**4 1*4* l***\nAdsmi-MHUs 2a 1 41 at 41 V*\nAir Reduction 1 It 70*4 JO-4 20-4\nAlaska Juneau 9 5\u20184 3-4 3V* V*\nAlleghany Cap. 2 2*4 2-4 2-4\nAllied 8tr\u00bb* 4 J7-* 27 27-4+\nAUle Chaim 1*0 1 27*4 27\u00ab4 27'* >4\nAmerada Pet 3* 1 i03>